        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Baseband 1 is only dedicated to the observation of the CO(1-0) emission line in NGC 7130. As explained above, from previous SEST data, we know the CO(1-0) line width is 85 km/s and, to properly reconstruct the line profile, we request a maximum channel average of (85 km/s)/6= 14.2 km/s. Then, the requested bandwidth is the bigger possible (1875 MHz) and the spectral resolution is the lower in FDM mode with a spectral avering =2 to lower the data rate. The resulting spectral resolution is 2.972 km/s which is appropriate for our goal being lower than the requested bandwidth for the noise calculation (14.2 km/s).

Basebands from 2 to 4 are dedicated for continuum observations necessary for a proper continuum substraction and calibration in the line analysis + continuum source emission analysis. TDM spectral setup is therefore selected. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We request the same angular resolution obtained in our previous VIMOS data (0.67 arcsec) because we aim to compare the spatial distribution of the CO emission line with this of H_alpha (VMOS data).

We estimate the largest angular size of source structure from our previous VIMOS data. In particular, we suggest the CO(1-0) emission will have the same spatial distribution of the H_alpha with source structures having angular size lower than 5 arcsec. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>---REQUESTED RMS----
Albrecht et al. 2007 observed the CO (1-0) emission line of NGC 7130 using SEST with an angular resolution resol_SEST = 45 arcsec. They found:
-) a peak temperature  of the CO(1-0) line T_peak(CO 1-0) = 163 mK which correspond to a peak flux density S_peak(CO 1-0) = 3.5 Jy;
-) a FWHM of the CO(1-0) line FWHM_(CO 1-0)= 85 km/s.
We suggest the CO emission will have a similar morphology observed in our previous VIMOS analysis of H_alpha (Bellocchi et al. 2012), e.g. 
it will extend up to D = 20 arcsec from the center. 
We request a S/N = 6 to ensure a reliable detection also of the weakest components.
We request an angular resolution of the new ALMA data resol_alma = 0.67 arcsec (see below for justification of the resol_alma). 
From comparison with the VIMOS H_alpha observations, we estimate that the new ALMA observations will map the 70% of observed flux with SEST, which is this due to components with largest angular size &lt; 5 arcsec.
Under the above assumptions, we estimate a 
rms = 0.7 *[S_peak(CO 1-0)/ (S/N)]x[(resol_Alma/D)^2] = 0.458 mJy 
to properly map the CO emission line over the estimated 20 arcsec region of NGC 7130 emission.

---REQUESTED BANDWIDTH FOR THE SENSITIVITY CALCULATION--- 
To good characterize the shape of the line (with FWHM=85 km/s) we need to sample the line in 6 channels of width (85 km/s)/6~ 14.2 km/s.  
This is the requested bandwidth for the sensitivity calculation.   

---CONTINUUM---
For a proper continuum subtraction and calibration purposes + continuum source emission analysis, we added 3 sidebands for the continuum.
The estimated global flux density was extrapolated from the available multi-frequency data available in literature (source: NED)</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
