    <prp:abstract>(Ultra) Luminous infrared galaxies [(U)LIRGs] host the most extreme star-forming events in the present Universe and are places where a significant fraction of the past star formation beyond z $\sim$ 1 has occurred. In particular, low-z (U)LIRGs offer a unique opportunity to study, at high linear resolution and signal-to-noise ratio (S/N), extreme SF events and compare them with those observed at high-z. The kinematic characterization of this population is important to constrain the processes that govern such events. In this proposal, we ask for high angular resolution (0.67 arcsec) ALMA band 3 observations to perform the CO(1-0) emission line and continuum analysis of a peculiar LIRG NGC 7130 at z=0.016. This is a starburst--AGN composite galaxy passing through a post-coalescence phase and showing multiband evidence of an outflow. Our requested data will resolve for the first time the molecular gas content in this object and they will be directly compared to our previous ionized gas (H${\alpha}$) observations done with VIMOS. This will also give important hints on the understanding of the AGN feedback and starburst--AGN connection in the (U)LIRG class of objects. </prp:abstract>
